Take-home Exercise 3: Be Weatherwise or Otherwise

I. Overview

II. Data Preparation

Installing R Packages

For this exercise, the following packages will be required to create useful visualizations of the data.

pacman::p_load(readxl, ggiraph, plotly, 
               patchwork, DT, tidyverse, gifski, gapminder, gganimate, ggplot2)

Data Sets

There are 5 data sets for this exercise, all of which are downloaded from the from Meteorological Service Singapore website. The data to be used is the mean temperature of the Changi region of Singapore during September in the years 1983, 1993, 2003, 2013, and 2023.

For the exercise at hand, the data has been merged into 1 data set which contains the average temperatures for each day of the month in the 5 years in question.

Temps <- read.csv("data/ChangiTemps.csv")
ggplot(Temps, aes(x = Temps[[4]], y = Temps[[9]])) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.7,
             show.legend = FALSE) +
  scale_size(range = c(2, 12)) +
  labs(title = 'Year: {frame_time}', 
       x = 'Day', 
       y = 'Mean Temperature (°C)') +
  transition_time(Year) + 
  ease_aes('linear')
gg <- ggplot(Temps, 
       aes(x = Temps[[4]], 
           y = Temps[[9]])) +
  geom_point(aes(frame = Year),
             alpha = 0.7, 
             show.legend = FALSE) +
  scale_size(range = c(2, 12)) +
  labs(x = 'Day', 
       y = 'Mean Temperature (°C)')
ggplotly(gg)
p <- ggplot(data=Temps,
            aes(x = Temps[[9]])) +
  geom_dotplot_interactive(
    aes(tooltip = Year,  # Specify the tooltip to show the year
        data_id = Year),  # Specify the data_id to use the year for identification
    stackgroups = TRUE,
    binwidth = 0.2,
    method = "histodot") +
  scale_y_continuous(NULL,
                     breaks = NULL)
girafe(
  ggobj = p,
  width_svg = 10,
  height_svg = 10*0.618,
  options = list(
    opts_hover(css = "fill: #202020;"),
    opts_hover_inv(css = "opacity:0.2;")
  )
)
plot_ly(data = Temps, 
        x = ~Day, 
        y = Temps[[9]], 
        color = ~Year)
